nal health agenda, and the hypnotic publicity given to "innocent" victims.Murphy's discussions of the many social and political confusions about AIDS are unified by his attempt to articulate the moral assumptions framing our interpretations of the epidemic. By understanding those assumptions, we will be in a better position to resist self-serving and invidious moralizing, reckless political response, and social censure of the sick and the dying.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAIDS (Disease)xGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aAIDS (Disease)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspects. 0aAIDS (Disease). 0aCelebrities. 0aContact tracing (Epidemiology). 0aDemography. 0aDentistry. 0aDiagnosis. 0aDiseases. 0aDrug abuse. 0aDrug addiction. 0aEconomics. 0aEpidemiology. 0aFederal aid. 0aGovernment aid. 0aHIV infections. 0aHealth planning. 0aHealth services accessibility. 0aHomosexuality. 0aHuman behavior. 0aHuman experimentation in medicine. 0aHumanities. 0aIatrogenic diseases. 0aImmunodiagnosis. 0aImmunologic diseases. 0aImmunological deficiency syndromes. 0aInternational cooperation. 0aLentivirus infections. 0aLiterature, Modern. 0aLiterature. 0aMass media. 0aMedical care. 0aMedical ethics. 0aMedical personnel. 0aMedical policy. 0aMental illness. 0aMortality. 0aNational health services. 0aPhilosophy. 0aPhysical sciences. 0aPhysicians. 0aPolitics, Practical. 0aPollution. 0aProfessional ethics. 0aPublic health. 0aResearch. 0aRetrovirus infections. 0aScience. 0aSerodiagnosis. 0aSexually transmitted diseases. 0aSlow virus diseases. 0aSocial change. 0aSocial control. 0aSocial psychology. 0aSocial sciences. 0aSociology. 0aTherapeutics. 0aVirus diseases. 0aVital statistics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics &